    "eyebrow": "Texicans in Early Texas History",
    "num": "01",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">01</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Texicans in Early Texas History</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Political Roles Before the Texas Revolution</h2><ul><li>Texicans held local political offices under Spanish and Mexican rule</li><li>They negotiated land grants and represented settler interests</li><li>Political allegiance shifted amid growing tensions with central Mexican government</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans were active participants in local governance, often mediating between Mexican authorities and Anglo settlers. Their political roles evolved as Mexico’s control weakened, leading to complex loyalties during the revolution [s2, s7]. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican leaders like Stephen F. Austin initially sought to work within Mexican political frameworks before supporting independence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify how Texican political roles changed from cooperation with Mexico to rebellion.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming all Texicans uniformly supported independence from the start.</p></div></div>",
