    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">02</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Texicans in Early Texas History</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Military Contributions of Texicans in the Texas Revolution</h2><ul><li>Texicans formed militias and volunteer companies</li><li>They played key roles in battles such as Gonzales and the Alamo</li><li>Military efforts reflected both local defense and broader independence goals</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans were instrumental in organizing and fighting in early conflicts of the Texas Revolution, balancing defense of their homes with aspirations for political change [s2, s7]. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The Texican volunteer company at the Battle of Gonzales famously resisted Mexican troops, marking the revolution’s start.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how Texican military actions reflected their political and social priorities.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the diversity of Texican motivations in military engagements.</p></div></div>",
