    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">07</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources and Historical Evidence</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Examining Texican Letters and Personal Accounts</h2><ul><li>Letters reveal personal experiences, motivations, and social relations</li><li>They provide perspectives often absent from official records</li><li>Analyzing tone and language helps uncover underlying sentiments</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Personal correspondence offers rich qualitative data on Texican life and attitudes, but requires careful reading to understand context and subtext [s15, s16]. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from a Texican soldier expresses conflicted feelings about fighting Mexican troops.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Interpret the emotional tone and political stance in a Texican letter excerpt.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking subtle cues or cultural references in personal documents.</p></div></div>",
