    "num": "10",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">10</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources and Historical Evidence</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Challenges in Interpreting Texican Historical Records</h2><ul><li>Language barriers: Spanish and English documents require translation and cultural understanding</li><li>Bias and perspective: Sources reflect authors’ interests and social positions</li><li>Incomplete records: Gaps and losses complicate historical reconstruction</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Interpreting Texican history demands awareness of linguistic, cultural, and archival challenges that affect source reliability and completeness [s10, s16]. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Some Texican voices, especially indigenous or lower-class, are underrepresented in surviving documents.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify potential limitations in a given primary source and suggest strategies to address them.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming historical records provide a complete or unbiased picture.</p></div></div>",
