      "secnum": "Deep Dive 10",
      "h": "Navigating Source Limitations in Texican History",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Interpreting Texican history demands awareness of linguistic, cultural, and archival challenges that affect source reliability and completeness [s10, s16].</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.fau.edu; tsl.texas.gov. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Language barriers: Spanish and English documents require translation and cultural understanding</li><li>Bias and perspective: Sources reflect authors’ interests and social positions</li><li>Incomplete records: Gaps and losses complicate historical reconstruction</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Some Texican voices, especially indigenous or lower-class, are underrepresented in surviving documents.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify potential limitations in a given primary source and suggest strategies to address them.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming historical records provide a complete or unbiased picture.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.fau.edu; tsl.texas.gov <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
