      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This checkpoint reinforces critical source evaluation skills essential for understanding Texican history [s10, s11].</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Review a provided Texican primary source excerpt</li><li>Identify author, purpose, and potential bias</li><li>Assess the source’s reliability and usefulness for historical analysis</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Determining that a government record may understate settler grievances due to official bias.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Write a brief evaluation of the source’s strengths and limitations.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Failing to consider the source’s context and intended audience.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup></p>"
