    "id": "slide49",
    "eyebrow": "Challenges in Texican Records",
    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Challenges in Texican Records</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Limitations in Demographic Data on Texicans</h2><ul><li>Sparse and inconsistent census records from early Texas periods</li><li>Underrepresentation of mixed-heritage individuals in official documents</li><li>Challenges in tracking population movements and family lineages</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Historical demographic data on Texicans is limited due to incomplete census efforts and inconsistent record-keeping, especially regarding mixed-heritage populations. This scarcity complicates understanding population dynamics and social structures. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Many Texican families of mixed Spanish, Native American, and Anglo descent were often recorded under a single ethnic category, obscuring their true cultural identities.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Consider how incomplete demographic data might affect interpretations of Texican community size and diversity.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming census data fully represents the Texican population without accounting for underreporting or categorization biases.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 13",
      "h": "Deep Dive: Demographic Data Challenges",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Historical demographic data on Texicans is limited due to incomplete census efforts and inconsistent record-keeping, especially regarding mixed-heritage populations. This scarcity complicates understanding population dynamics and social structures.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; libguides.fau.edu; tsl.texas.gov. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Sparse and inconsistent census records from early Texas periods</li><li>Underrepresentation of mixed-heritage individuals in official documents</li><li>Challenges in tracking population movements and family lineages</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Many Texican families of mixed Spanish, Native American, and Anglo descent were often recorded under a single ethnic category, obscuring their true cultural identities.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Consider how incomplete demographic data might affect interpretations of Texican community size and diversity.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming census data fully represents the Texican population without accounting for underreporting or categorization biases.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; libguides.fau.edu; tsl.texas.gov <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
    }
