      "h": "Deep Dive: Navigating Historical Uncertainties",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The gaps in demographic, sociocultural, and economic data create challenges for historians, potentially leading to incomplete or biased interpretations of Texican history and identity.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; tsl.texas.gov. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Incomplete narratives risk oversimplifying Texican identity</li><li>Potential marginalization of minority voices within Texican society</li><li>Challenges in constructing accurate social, economic, and political histories</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Without full demographic data, the diversity within Texican communities may be underestimated, affecting cultural and political analyses.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how acknowledging these gaps can improve historical research and interpretation.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring data limitations and presenting incomplete histories as definitive.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; tsl.texas.gov <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
